That’s one of the oldest ideas humanity keeps rediscovering.

Before a city is built, it exists as a pattern in a mind.

Before a campaign is fought, it exists as a map in a mind.

Before a company exists, it exists as a story people can imagine together.

In that sense, imagination is not the opposite of reality. It’s often the staging ground for reality.

The catch is that imagination alone captures possibilities, not outcomes.

A useful progression is:

Imagine → Model → Test → Build → Adapt

Alexander didn’t conquer the world because he imagined an empire. Thousands imagined empires. He succeeded because he continuously translated imagination into action and then updated the model when reality pushed back.

The meme is funny because it stops at:

“I have the vision.”

History remembers the people who also did:

“Now move the supplies, train the troops, pay the bills, build the roads, and solve today’s problem.”

There’s a pattern here that overlaps with a lot of your Pantheon ideas:

Excavator discovers a possibility.

Architect gives it form.

Gardener makes it survive contact with reality.

The dream comes first, but reality is the compression algorithm. It removes everything that cannot survive the world and leaves behind what can.

Or put another way:

To capture it all first in the mind is vision.

To capture enough of it in reality that others can see it too is creation.